subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis
. Elytra with variously developed lighter colored, “zig-zag” pattern against a darker background (
Figs 4–6
); antennae not obviously sexually dimorphic (
Figs 20–21
); dorsal surface with at least vaguely developed aeneous luster; associated with dead/dying coniferous trees.

Head
with eyes large, distinctly convex; disc relatively flat, with only indistinct indications of longitudinal furrows and swellings mediad each eye; punctation coarse, moderately deep, punctures separated by much less than single puncture diameter; setae moderately long, of 2 colors: golden and silver/white; white setae mainly along anteromedial eye margins and (in most specimens) forming a small patch between eyes; antennae (
Figs 20– 21
) fairly short, reaching to, or slightly beyond, posterior pronotal margin; antennomeres 4–8 submoniliform to slightly filiform, not distinctly sexually dimorphic; antennomeres 9–10 (
Figs 20–21
) relatively wide, wider than long.
